6.5 2b) Add a simple HTML page
Websites are created using many different programming languages and technologies. Technologies used to implement websites range from simple websites that use just HTML, CSS and JavaScript, to very complex websites that incorporate many other technologies. However, almost every website has a collection of the following 3 types of files

HTML files (usually end with .html)
These files contain the text of what is displayed on the website. Note that more complex websites often use techniques that generate a lof of the text for the website with other techniques.
CSS files (usually end with .css)
These files contain the instructions for the “styling” of the website - such as colors and fonts for different sections of the website.
JavaScript files (usually end with .js)
These files contain code that can make a website more interactive and reactive to user input.

We will create our first code file, index.html below. To create the file we can use one of the following two techniques:

6.5.1 Using a text editor to create our first code file
We want to create a file named index.html that contains the HTML code shown below. To do so you can create the file in a text editor such as Notepad (on Windows) or TextEdit ( in “plain text” mode - see above) on Mac. Make sure to save the file in the folder that you created above. To see the name of the folder where you should save the file you can type the Bash command pwd (pwd stands for Print Working Direcotry).
&lt;!doctype html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    &lt;meta charset="utf-8"&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Hello Site&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Hello, Git!&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;This is my first version.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;


6.5.2 ALTERNATIVE - use a bash command to create the file
Alternatively you can use the long command shown below in Bash directly to create the file.
Things to pay attention to:

The comamnd starts with the line cat &lt;&lt; EOF &gt; index.html.
The name of the file you are creating is specified after the &gt; sign. In this case, the name of the file is index.html.
The command ends with a line simply says EOF (no spaces before or after). The letters EOF stand for “End Of File”. Note that you can replace EOF on the first and last lines with any unique set of
The contents of the file you want to create is placed between the first line (i.e. cat ...) and the last line (i.e. EOF).

This technique can be used to create any text file you like.
cat &lt;&lt; EOF &gt; index.html
&lt;!doctype html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    &lt;meta charset="utf-8"&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Hello Site&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Hello, Git!&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;This is my first version.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
EOF
This technique is usefol for creating new files but is not useful when you want to edit an existing file. To do that the simplest thing to do is to use a text eidtor and described above.

6.7 3) Add CSS
FULL FILE CONTENT BELOW — style.css
body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; }
h1   { text-align: center; }
p    { color: #333; }
Link it in index.html (inside &lt;head&gt;):
&lt;link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css"&gt;
Commit:
git add style.css index.html
git commit -m "Add basic styles and link CSS"

6.8 4) Add JavaScript
FULL FILE CONTENT BELOW — app.js
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () =&gt; {
  console.log('Site loaded');
  const p = document.querySelector('p');
  p.textContent += ' (Now with JavaScript!)';
});
Link it in index.html before &lt;/body&gt;:
&lt;script src="app.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
Commit:
git add app.js index.html
git commit -m "Add simple JS to modify page text"

11.1 Configure Cursor to use it
The Playwright MCP server lets an MCP-capable client (e.g., Cursor) drive a real browser via Playwright tools. It exposes actions like navigate, click, type, evaluate JS, and more, using structured page snapshots (accessibility tree) rather than screenshots. :contentReferenceoaicite:0
Alternative (JSON style shown in some clients): json   {     "mcpServers": {       "playwright": {         "command": "npx",         "args": ["@playwright/mcp@latest"]       }     }   }

11.7 Workaround idea
If you’re comfortable with advanced setup, you could define two MCP entries — one “safe” and one “interactive” — and use the one you need:
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "playwright-dangerous": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["@playwright/mcp@latest"],
      "require_approval": "never"
    },
    "playwright-safe": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["@playwright/mcp@latest"],
      "require_approval": "always"
    }
  }
}
Then choose which server to use in your prompt:
“Use the playwright-safe server to open Wikipedia and summarize the first paragraph.”
Unfortunately, per-website approval rules are not supported.
Only per-server setting in mcp.json is supported.
Changing it via chat is not possible yet.

12.1 How to install / set up the MCP Server using the Supabase website

In your Supabase dashboard, find the MCP section and select the hosted server URL (typically https://mcp.supabase.com/mcp). :contentReferenceoaicite:8
Configure your AI tool (for example a client like Cursor) to point to that URL. For example in .cursor/mcp.json:
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "supabase": {
      "url": "https://mcp.supabase.com/mcp"
    }
  }
}
Optionally pass query parameters:

project_ref= to limit access to one project.
read_only=true to disable write operations.

Authenticate: For most clients the hosted server handles login automatically.
